I can integrate into it
with Workgroup Manager.

00:21:53.300 --> 00:21:56.440
I can check for machine and network
status for the help desk system.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:22:00.100
I can control how I image each one of
my labs through the help desk system

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:03.100
and I deal with package making as well,
which has always been the

00:22:03.100 --> 00:22:06.150
voodoo art that I've never been
able to get working properly.

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:10.270
Okay, so ARD2 runs on a client server
model as most of you know.

00:22:10.300 --> 00:22:12.200
It comes with a data
collection model as well.

00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:14.660
It currently stores data
in a centralized server.

00:22:14.740 --> 00:22:16.740
It would be nice if we could
leverage that in a future

00:22:16.740 --> 00:22:19.100
version to store it in one spot.

00:22:19.130 --> 00:22:21.790
And it runs in Postgres.

00:22:21.950 --> 00:22:24.060
which of course I knew nothing about.

00:22:24.130 --> 00:22:27.100
So when you look at the ARD information
that's stored in the Postgres table,

00:22:27.100 --> 00:22:29.230
this is just a screen
grab of some PHP stuff,

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:32.250
it's sorted into two separate tables,
a property name map table and

00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:34.110
a systems information table.

00:22:34.210 --> 00:22:37.140
When you break it down a little bit more,
you can see it stores the object name,

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:40.190
the property name,
and the property map ID.

00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:43.470
In the systems information
table it stores a little

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:44.590
bit more information though.

00:22:44.670 --> 00:22:48.500
We get the computer ID, the object name,
the property name, an item sequencer,

00:22:48.530 --> 00:22:51.480
the value,
and the time it was last updated.

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:55.430
So if we drill down some more,
you can see I get some really

00:22:55.430 --> 00:22:58.000
useful data about the information.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.580
So I can look at each machine
and see if there's a wireless

00:23:00.580 --> 00:23:04.350
card installed or if Apple Talk,
remember Apple Talk, is active.

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:06.990
I can look to see what
the boot ROM version is.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:08.230
I can look at the processor speed.

00:23:08.230 --> 00:23:09.720
I can look at the machine serial number.

00:23:09.830 --> 00:23:12.280
Some really granular data there.

00:23:14.330 --> 00:23:17.750
And because the stores are last updated,
I can run scans on this information

00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:21.200
and do a state check to see if
this information has changed.

00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:25.310
So if someone unplugs a network card
or someone plugs in a wireless card,

00:23:25.310 --> 00:23:27.340
if I compare the two
scans that I perform,

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:28.600
I have a change state.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:30.960
And that's what we leverage off.

00:23:31.350 --> 00:23:34.180
So we leverage completely off
the information that ARD stores.

00:23:34.200 --> 00:23:38.610
So you do need to set the system to
scan your machines on a specified basis.

00:23:38.670 --> 00:23:39.790
I do it every two hours.

00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:42.620
We're working with Apple to try and
make this a little bit more automated,

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:46.290
but you can set how often you want to
check the information on the machine.

