I don't touch anyone else's data,
so I take this information and put

00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:51.400
it into a centralized MySQL database.

00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:54.640
I'm also better at writing
MySQL stuff than I am Postgres.

00:23:54.690 --> 00:23:57.220
The goal for it was to
be a one-stop console.

00:23:57.220 --> 00:23:58.230
So it's all web-based.

00:23:58.250 --> 00:23:59.250
You can run it from BlackBerrys.

00:23:59.270 --> 00:24:00.520
You can run it from wireless palms.

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:01.840
You can run it from everything.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:04.900
So you can control it all
from a web-based console.

00:24:04.900 --> 00:24:07.000
And the tagline was
powerful for the powerful,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:11.170
simple enough for the
delegation or helper monkeys.

00:24:11.830 --> 00:24:16.110
So basically the workflow that we
follow is our faculty is called CCI.

00:24:16.120 --> 00:24:20.800
So we scan through the help desk and
look for the machines on the CCI subnet.

00:24:20.800 --> 00:24:24.700
So any machine that's got an ARD active,
the system scan will find it and store

00:24:24.700 --> 00:24:26.800
the information into the Postgres table.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:30.640
What I then do is suck that
information out from the Postgres

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:34.390
table in ARD and put it into
my own MySQL help desk database.

00:24:36.810 --> 00:24:37.840
Yes, I already said that.

00:24:37.870 --> 00:24:41.320
So when you look at the Postgres
information that's stored,

00:24:41.320 --> 00:24:44.310
it stores 79 separate pieces
of information currently about

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:45.300
each one of the machines.

00:24:45.300 --> 00:24:48.910
I tend to look for these seven,
but in the help desk system you can

00:24:48.910 --> 00:24:52.220
turn on and off which one of those 79
pieces of information you want tracked.

00:24:52.300 --> 00:24:54.670
So I look for the web sharing
status of the machine,

00:24:54.730 --> 00:24:58.300
the free RAM slots in the machine,
and I was telling a funny anecdote

00:24:58.300 --> 00:25:01.560
the other day of I found students
putting RAM into the machines because

00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:03.300
they wanted them to render faster.

00:25:03.300 --> 00:25:07.170
This system will actually check and
look at the status of the RAM in case

00:25:07.170 --> 00:25:09.300
normally people are stealing the RAM.

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:13.370
It looks for drive free space,
so you can specify a warning flag if the

00:25:13.450 --> 00:25:16.300
drive volume falls under 5% or 10% free.

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:19.630
You can look at the wireless
status of the machine.

00:25:19.630 --> 00:25:22.300
You can look at the SSS status.

00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:22.300
This is too hard.

00:25:22.360 --> 00:25:25.300
System versions and Samba sharing status.

00:25:25.300 --> 00:25:29.300
We use it to allocate machines into labs.

00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:32.240
One of the best things that
I ever did was paint the color

00:25:32.370 --> 00:25:35.380
of each one of our labs One wall
in the lab a different color,

00:25:35.410 --> 00:25:38.280
so I have a green lab, a blue lab,
a pink lab.

00:25:38.350 --> 00:25:41.120
It's an absolute wonderful tool
for help desk because the students

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:44.300
are trained to look at the wall
and tell us what room they're in.

00:25:45.830 --> 00:25:47.950
Honestly, I'm not kidding, genius.

00:25:47.950 --> 00:25:51.800
Sure you still get the students
who go the walls are white and you

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:54.420
say which wall and they go back and
they check and go no still white.

00:25:54.570 --> 00:25:57.740
They're not quite smart enough to look
