00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:00.110
Honestly, try it.

00:26:00.170 --> 00:26:01.540
It works.

00:26:01.540 --> 00:26:03.520
So what we allow to do
is to allow the machine,

00:26:03.710 --> 00:26:05.500
to allow how to allocate
machines to a lab.

00:26:05.500 --> 00:26:08.760
So from the help desk system we can
say any machine in Green Lab will

00:26:08.820 --> 00:26:12.090
be net booted from this image,
from this server with this image,

00:26:12.140 --> 00:26:13.200
and away it goes.

00:26:13.200 --> 00:26:17.070
The new version of the system is also
running with 10.4 multicasting as well.

00:26:17.290 --> 00:26:20.760
So you can say I want these three
servers to push all the network imaging.

00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:23.260
So what I can do is I can
delegate to a helper monkey.

00:26:23.260 --> 00:26:25.440
I can say, okay,
we're teaching a final class

00:26:25.540 --> 00:26:27.060
in the Green Lab at 2 o'clock.

00:26:27.060 --> 00:26:28.260
Reimage the lab.

00:26:28.680 --> 00:26:31.980
Previously that was a task as John would
say I'd have to send a swarm of monkeys

00:26:31.980 --> 00:26:35.500
with firewire drives to reimage them
or we'd have to do it ourselves and set

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:36.860
up the net restore service to do it.

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:40.020
What I can do now is send a
delegated admin to a web page to say,

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:43.650
and it goes from a pull down menu,
say pick Green Lab, pick the image,

00:26:43.650 --> 00:26:46.660
make it restore fast, click a button,
the machines will reboot.

00:26:46.660 --> 00:26:49.450
We use some custom SR hacks to
get it going and away we go.

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:51.510
So we've delegated some
tasks down really nicely.

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:57.320
My personal pet hatred was entering
computer lists into Workgroup Manager.

00:26:57.980 --> 00:27:01.410
It's a funny beast.

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:04.170
It forgets what it knows or
sometimes denies knowledge.

00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:07.070
What the help desk system allows
you to do is scan the machines in

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:10.620
with ARD and it clicks a button
called suck which works nicely

00:27:10.680 --> 00:27:12.960
for the auditing process as well.

00:27:14.140 --> 00:27:15.190
I just picked it at random.

00:27:15.310 --> 00:27:18.270
It clicks a button called Sark
and sucks all the computer list

00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:21.860
information out into the two text
files that Workgroup Manager uses.

00:27:21.860 --> 00:27:24.780
You export them to your desktop and
import them into Workgroup Manager and

00:27:24.780 --> 00:27:27.310
you've automatically got computer
list management based on the stuff

00:27:27.370 --> 00:27:28.860
that was set up in the help desk.

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:32.670
So for us to set up our labs,
we say Green Lab, allocate to Green Lab,

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:37.170
click Sark, information,
and then Workgroup Manager allows

00:27:37.550 --> 00:27:41.610
us to do our computer list
MCXing from the Green Lab.

00:27:44.230 --> 00:27:46.940
Okay, so yeah,
we do a lot of machine tracking.

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:49.310
As an IT manager, I like to be proactive.

00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:51.840
So what we do is do a lot of
the information and try to

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:53.200
do it on a proactive basis.

00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:56.390
So we specify how often
ARD scans our network.

00:27:56.510 --> 00:27:58.670
For this case, we do it every 60 minutes.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:02.300
And it searches the Postgres database
and it searches the MySQL database,

00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:03.400
looks for change dates.

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:05.610
I track back to 10
different change dates,

00:28:05.610 --> 00:28:09.610
so I can go back and say, well, hang on,
the last 10 times we scanned the network,

00:28:09.610 --> 00:28:12.410
this machine had no one using
it or it had all its RAM in.

00:28:12.420 --> 00:28:15.420
But now something has changed
and we can look at that.

00:28:15.470 --> 00:28:17.770
It looks for missing
machines and extra machines.

00:28:17.820 --> 00:28:20.220
So if a student brings a
machine in on the network and

00:28:20.220 --> 00:28:22.380
they've got ARD turned on,
we can know, we can find it,

00:28:22.450 --> 00:28:25.310
we can track where they were and
what they were doing with it.

00:28:25.590 --> 00:28:27.970
But the cool thing that it does
is the machine monitoring stuff.

00:28:28.030 --> 00:28:30.820
I like to be able to get out to the
machines or send a helper monkey to

00:28:30.820 --> 00:28:33.830
the machines when I know something's
wrong rather than waiting for

00:28:33.830 --> 00:28:36.100
someone to report something in to me.

00:28:36.110 --> 00:28:38.690
So what it does is it watches for
the change states and then alerts

00:28:38.830 --> 00:28:42.970
the helper monkeys or the help
desk system of the change state.

00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:45.340
One of the things that we'd see
a lot of was students would come

00:28:45.340 --> 00:28:47.670
in and disconnect the projectors
from the projector machines,

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:51.840
hook them up to their own laptop,
play Halo for six hours from 12 to 6 a.m.

00:28:51.900 --> 00:28:54.180
Go home and say they need an
extension for their assignment.

00:28:54.250 --> 00:28:56.160
The lecturer would come in,
I wouldn't know how to

00:28:56.230 --> 00:28:57.240
plug the projector back in.

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:58.500
They would scream that
nothing ever worked.

00:28:58.590 --> 00:28:59.690
My boss would scream at me.

00:28:59.740 --> 00:29:01.030
I'd scream at the help of monkeys.

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:04.990
It was just sad and I thought we
could do that in a better way.

00:29:05.370 --> 00:29:07.500
So we looked at how the students
were altering the machine settings.

00:29:07.500 --> 00:29:10.320
If students are going in and
turning web sharing on or

00:29:10.320 --> 00:29:13.540
SSH sharing on or Samba sharing on,
they're probably doing something

00:29:13.540 --> 00:29:14.300
they shouldn't be doing.

00:29:14.300 --> 00:29:16.450
We're looking for theft and damage.

00:29:16.560 --> 00:29:21.780
And my personal favorite of hatred,
I would go into labs and students would

00:29:21.780 --> 00:29:26.170
have taken the left mouse cable from one,
move it across, stretch the cable,

00:29:26.300 --> 00:29:28.400
pull the padlock,
put it into the other side,

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:30.300
and then try and use
the machine left-handed.

00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:31.700
And I would say,
"Why don't you use the mouse on

00:29:31.790 --> 00:29:33.960
the computer?" And they'd say,
"It doesn't work." And I'd say,

00:29:33.960 --> 00:29:36.730
"Did you tell anybody?" And they'd say,
"No,

00:29:36.730 --> 00:29:40.650
we thought you knew." Because we're IT,
we know everything.

00:29:40.650 --> 00:29:42.350
We don't know everything.

00:29:43.100 --> 00:29:47.140
So what the system does is proactively
tells me when it sees any change

00:29:47.140 --> 00:29:49.000
states in any of this information.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
It sends an iCal to
the nominated on-task,

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.000
on-job help desk person.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:57.100
So when the help desk person wakes
up in the morning and goes to work,

00:29:57.100 --> 00:29:59.360
in their little iCal is all
the computers that have found

00:29:59.360 --> 00:30:00.000
something wrong with them.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.000
So Green 12 schedules a job
for them to fix the mouse.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:07.000
It has an integrated knowledge base,
so it sends a hyperlink with this.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.040
So it says, you know,
the last four people who

00:30:09.150 --> 00:30:12.000
fixed this problem fixed it
by plugging the mouse back in.

00:30:14.210 --> 00:30:16.260
Oddly enough,
it didn't fix it for one time.

00:30:16.260 --> 00:30:18.070
I've never quite worked
out what that problem was.

00:30:18.300 --> 00:30:19.440
So it sends an iCal event.

00:30:19.640 --> 00:30:22.210
That's great for me because I can see
an overview of the helper monkeys.

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:24.850
It's great for my boss because he
can see an overview of the helper

00:30:24.940 --> 00:30:27.790
monkeys and ask me what I'm doing.

00:30:28.380 --> 00:30:29.860
Because this is a,
and I didn't talk about this,

00:30:29.860 --> 00:30:31.980
this is a completely fully
functional help desk system.

00:30:32.010 --> 00:30:35.270
We're talking about job tickets,
asset tracking, the whole thing.

00:30:35.270 --> 00:30:38.700
It's got an F12 dashboard widget
so students on the machines,

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:42.000
when we roll to Tiger on the desktop,
when the students hit F12 they'll be able

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:43.580
to log their own jobs into the system.

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:46.800
It automatically logs that into
the help desk system so I can get a

00:30:46.850 --> 00:30:48.660
feel for the trend of the machine.

00:30:48.660 --> 00:30:52.540
If the machine's mouse keeps breaking and
the staff keep plugging it back in again,

00:30:52.540 --> 00:30:54.140
it might not just be the mouse.

00:30:54.140 --> 00:30:57.000
We might have some USB problems so
I can get a state of the machine.

00:30:57.420 --> 00:31:01.620
It sends an email to me and our help
desk team so everyone knows all the

00:31:01.620 --> 00:31:03.360
different jobs that they're across.

00:31:03.400 --> 00:31:06.570
It can do a combination.

00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:07.740
The management team adore it.

00:31:07.870 --> 00:31:09.750
We can keep track of
what our staff are doing.

00:31:09.750 --> 00:31:11.900
We're so quickly to the desktop,
it's amazing.

00:31:11.900 --> 00:31:14.290
So the students don't know things
are broken most of the time

00:31:14.290 --> 00:31:15.600
before we've even fixed them.

00:31:15.600 --> 00:31:20.820
And I had it sending SMSs,
but I got begged to have that turned off.

00:31:20.820 --> 00:31:25.710
So when the mouse got unconnected in G14,
the helper monkey would get a page.

00:31:25.760 --> 00:31:28.600
But at 3 in the morning they didn't
seem to care so much about that.

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:32.600
So if you want to do that,
you can actually turn that on as well.

00:31:32.600 --> 00:31:35.560
So the sample alerts that I look at,
as I have 3 minutes to go.

00:31:35.610 --> 00:31:36.770
I look at drive free space.

00:31:36.790 --> 00:31:40.600
So I specify I want to know every
machine on my network that I'm managing

00:31:40.600 --> 00:31:42.600
that has less than 10% drive free.

00:31:42.630 --> 00:31:46.600
Remember I can track back and I can
see where the drive space has gone.

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:48.520
So I can look at states, okay,
it's all been stored in the

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:50.520
correct folder or hang on,
somebody has snuck something in

00:31:50.520 --> 00:31:51.600
that they shouldn't have done.

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:53.600
I can change an SSH status.

00:31:53.600 --> 00:31:54.600
I look at the system version.

00:31:54.600 --> 00:31:57.850
That's great for managing academics
machines when they start to install

00:31:57.850 --> 00:32:00.600
new versions of the operating system
and claim they didn't do that.

00:32:00.600 --> 00:32:02.590
We can say, well, hang on.

00:32:02.700 --> 00:32:04.600
So that's what you did.

00:32:04.600 --> 00:32:06.560
We look at the free RAM slots
in case people are nicking RAM.

00:32:06.760 --> 00:32:09.600
Web sharing, window sharing,
wireless status and mouse.

00:32:09.600 --> 00:32:13.600
But this can work for any of
the 79 features that ARD tracks.

00:32:13.600 --> 00:32:16.220
So if you find people are
randomly turning Apple Talk on,

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:17.600
you can go and ask them why.

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:22.080
The black voodoo art of package making
is handled by the help desk system.

00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:26.070
One of the tasks that is always
bumped up the scale to tier 2

00:32:26.180 --> 00:32:28.120
or tier 3 is making packages.

00:32:28.120 --> 00:32:31.410
What we've done is written a whole
pile of code that leverages the

00:32:31.520 --> 00:32:33.450
package maker command line tool.

00:32:33.600 --> 00:32:36.730
So it runs a series of scripts and
makes its own packages that the

00:32:36.760 --> 00:32:38.920
helper monkeys can push out with ARD.

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:41.040
And that's a pretty cool demo,
which I don't have time for.

00:32:41.080 --> 00:32:42.890
So, for example,
I can get the helper monkeys

00:32:42.890 --> 00:32:44.220
to change a desktop pattern.

00:32:44.220 --> 00:32:46.410
I can get them to set the
volume on different machines

00:32:46.430 --> 00:32:49.180
or a whole lab of machines,
which is great when you need to

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:52.520
reboot a lab which is next to a
lab which is doing a hearing test.

00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:55.320
And it builds a library of scripts.

00:32:55.320 --> 00:32:57.770
So if you need to go back and say, oh,
I remember that script that

00:32:57.770 --> 00:33:00.150
we used to repurpose our OD,
remake the package for

00:33:00.150 --> 00:33:01.620
me and send it back out.

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:06.540
And it basically allows us to
have a full automation process.

