00:36:23.690 --> 00:36:25.780
It is very popular.

00:36:25.780 --> 00:36:28.280
There are a lot of people who use it,
and it is open source.

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:32.230
And there are several people
who are modifying the code

00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:33.860
for their particular needs.

00:36:33.860 --> 00:36:39.460
It runs on many Unix platforms,
so if you don't have an X server,

00:36:39.530 --> 00:36:43.470
any other sort of Macintosh server,
you can run it on Linux or several

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:46.130
BSD variants if that's what you have.

00:36:46.150 --> 00:36:50.380
SSL is supported,
so you can have encryption on

00:36:50.380 --> 00:36:52.040
all your network transfers.

00:36:52.040 --> 00:36:54.180
And it's very easy.

00:36:54.180 --> 00:36:56.220
You can get very detailed configurations.

00:36:56.220 --> 00:37:00.280
Not easy,
but it's very-- it is easy to specify

00:37:00.420 --> 00:37:02.070
exactly what machine gets what.

00:37:02.140 --> 00:37:06.150
So where Steven was talking about,
he has 16 standard images.

00:37:06.160 --> 00:37:09.990
That actually is fairly
easy to do with RadMine.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:11.000
I'll talk about that.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:14.040
Also,
it's very detailed hard disk management.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:18.370
So every single file on the hard
disk is cataloged and stored on the

00:37:18.370 --> 00:37:22.660
centralized server so that you have
access-- you basically know exactly

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:24.080
what's on your computer's hard drives.

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:27.280
And you can-- I mean,
that's often how I debug problems.

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:28.910
Someone says there's a
problem with this machine.

00:37:28.930 --> 00:37:33.100
I go to the server half the time before
I actually go to the client machine to

00:37:33.130 --> 00:37:35.200
see if there's actually a difference.

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:37.590
'Cause most of the time,
I can see exactly what's on the

00:37:37.590 --> 00:37:39.360
machine just by looking at the server.

00:37:40.730 --> 00:37:45.280
So the command line tools,
the main one that resides on the server,

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:47.380
that runs on the server, is RadMine.

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:48.940
It's what talks to the client tools.

00:37:48.940 --> 00:37:52.220
And so the RadMine's
process is always running.

00:37:52.220 --> 00:37:56.180
It opens a port,
and it listens for the client tools.

00:37:56.180 --> 00:37:59.930
The client tools, fsstiff,
it doesn't talk over the network.

00:38:00.060 --> 00:38:02.480
Basically,
all it does is it scans the hard disk.

00:38:02.480 --> 00:38:03.620
It's kind of like a camera.

00:38:03.620 --> 00:38:06.900
It just takes a snapshot
of the hard disk.

00:38:06.900 --> 00:38:08.350
And it's configurable.

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:11.600
You can tell it, you know,
what exactly to look at.

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:13.550
You can tell it to look at the
whole hard disk or specific

00:38:13.650 --> 00:38:16.140
folders or just one file.

00:38:16.140 --> 00:38:19.770
LApply undoes changed files.

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:21.580
LApply does talk over the network.

00:38:21.580 --> 00:38:24.670
It talks to the RadMine server.

00:38:24.940 --> 00:38:27.910
LCreate uploads changed
files to the server.

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:29.850
Again, it talks over the network again.

00:38:29.920 --> 00:38:33.550
I'll talk more about what
LApply and LCreate do.

00:38:33.650 --> 00:38:39.450
KT Check, it talks to the server,
and it downloads descriptions from the

00:38:39.450 --> 00:38:44.140
server basically a description that
says what should be on the machine.

00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:46.140
Their descriptions are
called transcripts,

00:38:46.140 --> 00:38:49.340
which is part of an overload.

00:38:49.340 --> 00:38:55.720
So fsstiff,
how does it know what is changed?

00:38:55.820 --> 00:38:58.710
Basically, fsstiff,
the first thing you do is you're

00:38:58.720 --> 00:39:00.930
going to scan the whole hard disk.

00:39:01.380 --> 00:39:06.490
And that scan becomes what's
called your base load.

00:39:06.500 --> 00:39:09.800
When you scan your hard disk,
you basically have no idea

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:10.790
what's on the hard disk.

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:13.600
It just scans the whole file
system from beginning to end,

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:15.000
and then it's cataloged.

00:39:15.010 --> 00:39:16.290
Everything's there.

00:39:16.410 --> 00:39:21.280
So now it knows what was there
at that time it was scanned.

00:39:21.320 --> 00:39:23.380
Then what you do when you
want to make an image of that,

00:39:23.380 --> 00:39:26.720
you basically just upload that
all to the server all at once.

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:31.090
And so you've basically got a copy
of that file system on the server.

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:34.720
All scans after that first
scan are differences.

00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:40.030
And they are -- let's see --
they're uploaded -- they're

00:39:40.030 --> 00:39:42.990
uploaded with Lcreate,
and they are called overloads.

00:39:43.080 --> 00:39:45.000
So you have your base load,
and then you have

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:45.990
overloads on top of that.

00:39:46.130 --> 00:39:49.800
So like with Steven,
where he has the 16 standard images,

00:39:50.040 --> 00:39:54.490
what we do, we have one standard image,
and then we have all kinds of

00:39:54.490 --> 00:40:00.660
overloads for each different
configuration that we want to have.

00:40:00.820 --> 00:40:05.520
So when I scan with fsstiff,
there's two ways I can scan.

00:40:05.520 --> 00:40:07.730
I can scan -- so I've got my base load.

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:09.130
I scan the whole hard disk.

00:40:09.200 --> 00:40:12.830
And then I can get differences
from that first scan.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:15.620
Those differences can either
be uploaded with Lcreate or

00:40:15.620 --> 00:40:18.110
they can be undone with Lapply.

00:40:18.180 --> 00:40:22.120
And so the new files are deleted,
and the missing and modified files,

00:40:22.120 --> 00:40:23.770
they're redownloaded from the server.

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:25.980
So some examples.

00:40:26.060 --> 00:40:30.160
The simple example,
create your first scan, your base load.

00:40:30.160 --> 00:40:33.420
You change something with
the finders or any other app.

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:35.600
You just change stuff, you know,
create a bunch of new folders.

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:37.010
That's the easiest example.

00:40:37.020 --> 00:40:38.900
Then you scan the whole hard disk again.

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:42.390
And then you're going to get
a list of what's changed.

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:44.800
Those basically -- every single
file that you've modified,

00:40:44.800 --> 00:40:48.380
you can then remove
those files with Lapply.

00:40:48.380 --> 00:40:52.940
You run Lapply specifying, you know,
here's the changes that I found.

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:56.490
And Lapply will go and it'll just
start deleting all the files or

00:40:56.490 --> 00:41:00.410
redownloading files as it sees it needs.

00:41:00.510 --> 00:41:04.590
So if you deleted a file,
it will redownload it from the server.

00:41:09.830 --> 00:41:11.920
Okay, a more detailed example.

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:14.680
So bringing a machine to a known state.

00:41:14.680 --> 00:41:19.180
So I can take any one of your guys'
laptops and I don't have to know what

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:21.810
was on your laptop before I get it.

00:41:21.810 --> 00:41:22.780
It doesn't even matter.

00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:28.960
I can download my descriptions of my
machines from my server on your machine.

00:41:28.960 --> 00:41:32.990
With those descriptions,
I can then scan your whole hard disk,

00:41:33.160 --> 00:41:37.540
find what's different on your hard
disk with what I have on my hard disks,

00:41:37.600 --> 00:41:40.930
and I can find every single
file that's different.

00:41:40.940 --> 00:41:46.440
So then what I can do is basically
I can undo all those differences so that

00:41:46.440 --> 00:41:52.440
I can basically borgify any one of your
laptops into one of my lab machines.

00:41:52.480 --> 00:41:52.740
So that's a great way to do it.

00:41:52.740 --> 00:41:53.180
So I can download my descriptions of my
machines from my server on your machine.

00:41:53.180 --> 00:41:55.740
So I can download my descriptions
of my machines from my

00:41:55.750 --> 00:41:58.450
server on your hard disk,
find what was on your hard disk,

00:41:58.450 --> 00:42:00.450
find what was different
on your hard disk,

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:02.590
and I can then scan your whole hard disk.

00:42:03.100 --> 00:50:50.500
[Transcript missing]

00:50:51.500 --> 00:50:52.440
This always throws me off.

00:50:52.630 --> 00:50:54.620
When at the login panel.

00:50:54.620 --> 00:50:55.700
Okay.

00:50:55.700 --> 00:50:59.010
Yeah, so that's what I just described.

00:50:59.020 --> 00:51:01.490
When logged in,
what I really meant was when

00:51:01.660 --> 00:51:04.130
you're logged in the machine,
we have an icon that we double

00:51:04.130 --> 00:51:07.700
click and then we'll log the machine
out and begin running RadMine.

00:51:07.700 --> 00:51:11.250
So both at login and logout,
we can run RadMine and basically

00:51:11.250 --> 00:51:14.410
we can leave the machine and
not worry that someone will

00:51:14.410 --> 00:51:15.750
come and interrupt the process.

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:19.770
Also, we can do this remotely so that we
can be anywhere we want and we can

00:51:19.900 --> 00:51:21.500
start running RadMine on our machines.

00:51:21.500 --> 00:51:25.680
And then also we run it at a
specified time with Cron so that

00:51:25.820 --> 00:51:30.230
all of our machines everywhere,
they just update themselves periodically,

00:51:30.230 --> 00:51:31.150
automatically.

00:51:31.240 --> 00:51:34.980
And then we like to ensure that
RadMine finishes by running

00:51:34.980 --> 00:51:36.070
it at startup and this stops.

00:51:36.180 --> 00:51:39.160
I remember in the old OS9 days,
students would come and just

00:51:39.340 --> 00:51:41.960
force restart the machines
because it was running maintenance

00:51:41.960 --> 00:51:44.350
and they wanted to use it,
so they forced restart it and it would

00:51:44.350 --> 00:51:45.400
boot up and they could then use it.

00:51:45.460 --> 00:51:50.280
So we run RadMine at startup and
that's pretty much solved that.

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:53.580
I don't think I see our students
doing this anymore ever.

00:51:55.300 --> 00:53:58.400
[Transcript missing]

00:53:58.940 --> 00:54:02.920
So in OS 9 days,
users would come to the machine and

00:54:02.920 --> 00:54:05.410
they would mess stuff up constantly.

00:54:05.580 --> 00:54:07.610
The next user would come in and, oh,
the machine doesn't work,

00:54:07.710 --> 00:54:08.620
and they would blame us.

00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:11.410
But by managing the home
folders at every login,

00:54:11.410 --> 00:54:14.260
we are pretty much
guaranteed it always works.

00:54:14.350 --> 00:54:18.910
It's also secure and private,
so what the last user did isn't going

00:54:18.910 --> 00:54:21.440
to be available to the next user.

00:54:21.440 --> 00:54:24.760
We do cache the home folders,
so basically we move them

00:54:24.760 --> 00:54:28.380
to a private location,
and when that user comes back,

00:54:28.490 --> 00:54:28.780
they can add them to the next user.

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:31.440
We can access their old files,
and this is especially important

00:54:31.600 --> 00:54:32.740
if the machine restarts.

00:54:32.740 --> 00:54:34.900
That way their files aren't deleted
and they can never get them again.

00:54:34.900 --> 00:54:38.990
I have had a student cry
because she lost her term paper,

00:54:39.020 --> 00:54:42.240
so that was very
important for us to have.

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:47.830
The security audits,
we scan our computers for

00:54:47.830 --> 00:54:51.080
world-writable files and folders
and they are reported to us.

00:54:51.080 --> 00:54:56.450
This is part of the reason why we
have the something blank apps webpage.

00:54:56.450 --> 00:54:57.980
I don't know if anyone
is familiar with that.

00:54:58.160 --> 00:55:04.630
Yeah, so we know a lot about this
because we watch for it.

00:55:04.800 --> 00:55:09.180
I remember when we first started watching
for the writable files and folders,

00:55:09.180 --> 00:55:12.970
I mean, we thought we were doing good
and we just found our hard

00:55:13.160 --> 00:55:14.470
disk was just full of them.

00:55:14.500 --> 00:55:17.410
If you aren't watching,
you're going to have all

00:55:17.410 --> 00:55:19.140
kinds of them basically.

00:55:19.140 --> 00:55:23.130
We had to go through great steps to
stop our apps from doing this and so

00:55:23.130 --> 00:55:27.730
there's just too many out there that
not only installs world-writable but

00:55:27.930 --> 00:55:28.020
make sure that they're not going to
be used for writing files and folders.

00:55:28.040 --> 00:55:31.610
So many of them require
world-writable files and folders

00:55:31.660 --> 00:55:33.440
in order to actually run.

00:55:33.480 --> 00:55:36.820
We also check open from our
password because that is the only

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:40.250
stop gate you have from users
having root access if you want to

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:44.250
stop them from having root access,
which is highly recommended.

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:47.170
And again, same scenario.

00:55:47.330 --> 00:55:50.680
When we first started doing this,
we thought we were good and we were

00:55:50.770 --> 00:55:54.370
just horrified how many machines
had open from our password off.

00:55:54.400 --> 00:55:57.900
Then we also contact a web
server for theft prevention.

00:55:58.040 --> 00:56:01.590
We manage printer settings so that
one user can't modify the printer

00:56:01.710 --> 00:56:05.630
settings for the next user so the
settings are restored to every login.

00:56:05.640 --> 00:56:09.450
And then we also restore resolution
settings so that if a user

00:56:09.450 --> 00:56:13.860
